<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1887-07-08T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1887-07-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="468" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d468">
                        <head>No. 13.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Sir <persName type="from">L. S.
                                    Sackville West</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Bayard</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1887-07-08"><hi rend="italic">July</hi> 8, 1887</date>.
                                (Received July 9.)</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to your note of the 12th
                            April, stating that the records of the judicial proceedings in the cases
                            of the British vessels <pb facs="0799" n="1757" xml:id="pg_1757"/>
                            seized in the Bering Sea had been received, I have the honor, to inform
                            you that the Marquis of Salisbury has instructed me to request you to be
                            good enough to furnish me with a copy of the same for the information of
                            Her Majesty’s Government.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">L. S. Sackville
                            West.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>